<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-497-532  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 497 532.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  May 1990 v30 n5 p16(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Improving work performance.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sisson, Gary R.; Swanson, Richard A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Performance improvement is based upon performance goals, andinvolves taking systematic action.andP;  Many alternative workperformance improvement programs are available, but thesegenerally lack completeness and harmony.andP;  A seven-phase processfor improving work performance is presented: articulate purpose,specify performance, determine needs, diagnose causes, prescribeactions, implement actions, and evaluate performance.andP;  This simplemethodology can improve the performance of an individual or of agroup.andP;  Quality of work environment, level of aptitude, degree ofmotivation, and amount of expertise can all cause discrepanciesbetween the desired performance and the current level of workperformance.andP;  Performance improvement depends on proper diagnosisof such causes.andP;  Action guides outlining steps for improving workperformance are included.andP;  These include determining needs,diagnosing causes, prescribing actions, and evaluatingperformance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MethodsPerformance ImprovementEmployeeManagement.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Work performance factors, levels, and key questions. (table)Performance improvement methods at each phase. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>